### 7. How CSS Custom Properties Get Applied

The mechanism works in two layers:

**Layer 1: CSS file (static)** -- `apps/web/src/index.css` is unchanged. Its `:root { ... }` block defines light-mode defaults for all 24 CSS variables. The `@variant dark { ... }` block inside `:root` defines dark-mode overrides that activate when `.dark` is on `<html>`.

**Layer 2: Inline styles (dynamic)** -- The `useTheme` hook sets/removes CSS custom properties directly on `document.documentElement.style`. Because inline styles have higher specificity than stylesheet rules, any property set by the theme overrides the CSS file. When a theme does NOT override a property, it is removed from the inline style, allowing the CSS file's value to take effect.

For `t3-light` and `t3-dark`: These themes set only the new domain-specific variables (sidebar, editor, terminal, status-bar) that do not exist in the CSS file. All other variables fall through to the CSS file, so visually these themes look identical to the current light/dark modes.

For `t3-midnight`: This theme overrides nearly all variables, creating a completely different palette on top of the dark base.

